  "journal_summary": "ONTOLOGY CHARACTERISTICS: The Alarm Ontology comprises 28 core classes, 64 properties (43 object properties, 21 data properties), and 19 predefined states. The ontology instantiates 204 individuals with an instance-to-class ratio of 7.3:1, distributed across clinical (37, 18.1%), device (109, 53.4%), and alarm-specific (58) domains.\n\nALARM MODELING: The approach employs 0 Alert Condition Descriptions and 6 Alert Condition States, operationalized through 494 condition specifications. The modeling distinguishes between 228 explicitly asserted conditions and 197 computationally inferred conditions (ratio 228:197), connected via 0 \"requires\" and 0 \"implies\" relations.\n\nCLINICAL COVERAGE: Domain coverage encompasses 7 major physiological domains (Ecg, Oxygen, Pressure, Temperature, Cardiac, Co2, Rate) and 7 medical device categories (Transducer, Ventilator, Capnography, Monitor, Oximeter, Probe, Sensor), supporting comprehensive intensive care monitoring scenarios.\n\nINTEROPERABILITY: Standards alignment includes 8 entities with SNOMED CT codes and 0 with IEEE 11073 MDC codes, organized across 21 modular namespaces for maintainability and reuse.\n\nCOMPUTATIONAL CHARACTERISTICS: The complete ontology contains 1,569 RDF triples with 352 unique subjects and 60 unique predicates, yielding an average branching factor of 4.46 and ontology density of 4.46."
